"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, I want to give a tour of my worm pile. So after composting, uh, which takes about two months, uh, the material that I put in there is completely broken down, all the heat has left it because the thermophilic bacteria have no more food to consume, all the materials broken down, but it still needs to cure. It still needs all the other larger, non prokaryotic, uh, eucharatic, and and all the larger forms of life to get in there and start working their magic within that too to get integrated back into the community of bugs. And so that's my curing area. Now, this can happen on the beds if you have a very active decay cycle in your soil, but no matter how you do it, adding fresh compost is going to borrow some of the biology from your bed for a little bit until it replenishes and fills that in. So I like to get a head start on it, and also my compost is a little bit woody, and so putting it to the curing pile for about three to four months and letting the earthworms and the dung beetles and all the other little guys work on that and gals, work on that, it will break it down to a finer consistency. And as that happens, I slowly rake off all of the larger matter into back into the composting area, and then use all that dirt. So here's what's going on. Over here is my existing pile that I'm borrowing from. Now, if you'll look carefully, getting down on it, there's a ridge that's about a foot high, going all the way through. You can see where I've cleared out about half of it. That's down to the clay, and then over here, where there's a lot of things growing on it. That's all my good compost. That's about a foot tall. On the other side is the compost that I'm putting down right now. And this I'm not borrowing from, I'm just adding to, and I'll continue adding to this for about another two months. And then I'll shut this one off and borrow it again from this in another two, three months. But I'll be slowly raking. If you look at the debris, it's much heavier on this pile because it's newer. And all of that debris is coming to the surface as the small particles drop for into it and down, and the big particles wind up. And the chickens and the rain and the wind help with all that. Anyway, thanks y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody, I want to give a tour of my worm pile.\",\n      \"start\": 1.6,\n      \"end\": 6.16,\n      \"duration\": 4.56,\n      \"confidence\": 0.993,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 1.6,\n          \"end\": 1.92,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 0.982\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 1.92,\n          \"end\": 2.0,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 0.999\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 2.08,\n          \"end\": 2.24,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 2.24,\n          \"end\": 2.48,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 2.48,\n          \"end\": 2.64,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \",\",\n          \"start\": 2.64,\n          \"end\": 2.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.928\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" I\",\n          \"start\": 2.8,\n          \"end\": 3.04,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" want\",\n          \"start\": 3.04,\n          \"end\": 3.2,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.991\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" to\",\n          \"start\": 3.2,\n          \"end\": 3.28,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.